^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|There are many misconceptions in bridge that hurts a lot of players in their bidding and play. But, in my opinion, the ##1 misconception is that declarer should draw trump as soon as possible. When I ask students how often they draw trump first, their usual estimate is in the vicinity of 75%.|
PG| ***** 2 ***** |


AT|

Why do so many players believe this? Is it because their first bridge teacher gave them very easy hands where they didn't have to do anything except draw trump and take the obvious tricks? Or, did their friends tell them that the first thing to do is “get the kiddies off the street”? Or, they can't forget the time they went down in a cold contract because they didn't immediately draw trump and a defender ruffed one of their winners.|
PG| ***** 3 ***** |


AT|

I understand the above. However, on most hands, is it correct draw trump ASAP?|
PG| ***** 4 ***** |


AT| No way. The truth is, it is usually wrong to draw trump first. I estimate that declarer should draw trump ^*Bat most 40% of the time^*N. It would be absurd to say that drawing trump first is never correct. However, there are many reasons not to draw trump as soon as possible. Here are a few of them:|
PG| ***** 5 ***** |


cs|1|cp|4|AT|
^-{  You need to ruff losers in dummy  }|
PG| ***** 6 ***** |


AT|

{  You must preserve entries in the trump suit in order to develop a long suit  }|
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


AT|

{  You want to set up an end play  }|
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


AT|

{  You are eager to set up a side suit which will allow you to discard losers  }
^-|
PG| ***** 9 ***** |


cp||at|^B@2
After I explain this, I try to reinforce my point to my classes with the following. The next time you declare a suit contract, if you are so sure it's right to draw trump first that you would be willing to bet $100 on it, go ahead. But, if you are not that sure, you should not draw trump ASAP. |
PG| ***** 10 ***** |


cp|4|AT|

^-{  In other words, when in doubt, don't draw trump first  }
^-|
